<HEADLINE>
<P>
TOP LAWMEN MEET TO MAP A DRUG WAR; 
</P>
<P>
NARCOTICS: RESORT ATMOSPHERE BELIES BUSINESSLIKE ATTITUDE OF STATE, FEDERAL AND 
MILITARY OFFICIALS WHO DISCUSS STRATEGY AT TWO-DAY CONFERENCE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GEORGE RAMOS, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
PALM SPRINGS 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The conventioneers came from as far away as Zapata County, Tex., 170 strong. 
They tended to wear cowboy boots and colorful summer shirts, and steered clear 
of the swimming pool and golf courses. They had come not for sunshine, but to 
huddle in private rooms and plot a war. 
</P>
<P>
In a two-day conference that ended Tuesday, top law enforcement officials from 
throughout the Sun Belt, including Los Angeles County Sheriff Sherman Block and 
his counterparts from Orange, San Diego, Riverside, San Bernardino and Imperial 
counties, met with ranking state, federal and military authorities to map 
strategy over how best to stop the flow of illegal drugs into the United States 
from south of the border. 
</P>
<P>
"This is the first war I've planned in a fancy hotel, but . . . this is one war 
we aim to win," said a Texas Ranger, who was dressed in a loud Hawaiian shirt. 
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which was organized by Block and the California National Guard, 
was described as significant by its participants because it marked the first 
time that so many government combatants in the drug war actually met to share 
experiences, information and strategy. 
</P>
<P>
The Palm Springs meeting followed pledges in September by President Bush and 
Defense Secretary Dick Cheney to commit the military to the drug war. It was 
particularly gratifying for Block, who has criticized the federal government's 
level of support for local authorities fighting the illegal drug trade from 
Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
"This is a real beginning," Block said moments after standing up during an 
opening conference session to praise the presence of Michael Wermuth, a deputy 
assistant defense secretary. 
</P>
<P>
Since the Bush Administration proposed military participation in the drug 
fight, the burden of the Pentagon's involvement has fallen not on full-time 
regular troops but on part-time National Guard units in each state 
</P>
<P>
The mood of the gathering was upbeat as veteran drug fighters from inner-city 
Los Angeles swapped business cards with reservists from the New Mexico National 
Guard. The attendees were conspicuous in the resort setting with their 
uniformly short haircuts and pale complexions. 
</P>
<P>
Much of the business was kept secret. The meeting's organizers refused to say 
what was discussed in so-called "breakout meetings" that were closed to news 
reporters. Nor would they say when the new coordinated drug war would commence. 
</P>
<P>
"Nobody tells you everything in a war," said one grizzled federal agent from 
New Mexico, who like the other conventioneers wore a name tag but asked that 
his identity not be published. "Let the drug lords find out when we put them 
behind bars." 
</P>
<P>
One ranking official of the U.S. Customs Service, while declining to discuss 
specifics in the closed-door sessions, said civilian authorities seemed 
interested in determining how best they can use military equipment and 
personnel. Of particular interest was how military intelligence can be used. 
</P>
<P>
"If we merged intelligence from several sources, including the military, just 
think how much more effective we can be in making seizures and arrests," the 
customs official said. 
</P>
<P>
Despite the optimism of those in attendance, it seemed evident that this new 
war may have some rocky moments. 
</P>
<P>
Lt. Gen. Herbert Temple, who heads the National Guard Bureau in Washington, 
went out of his way to tell the civilian officials that the reserve military 
units were not the ultimate players in the government's commitment to fight 
drugs. 
</P>
<P>
"We are not in charge of the war on drugs," he said. "You are. Our job is to 
help you win it." 
</P>
<P>
Temple also said he was hesitant to commit reservists to certain tasks, such as 
searching cargo containers for illegal drugs, since that is not a "military 
duty these folks were trained to do." 
</P>
<P>
He said he would consult with civilian authorities on how best to deploy Guard 
units. 
</P>
<P>
California Gov. George Deukmejian addressed the group at its closing luncheon 
at the Radisson Palm Springs Resort Hotel. 
</P>
<P>
"While there are some pessimists who want to run up the white flag and 
surrender, there is no question in my mind that this defeatist attitude is dead 
wrong," Deukmejian said. "The health, safety and quality of our society depends 
on it. 
</P>
<P>
"We have a long, difficult, arduous fight ahead of us. But let me say, it is 
worth it." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
MEETINGS; LAW ENFORCEMENT OFFICERS; DRUG TRAFFICKING -- UNITED STATES; DRUG 
ENFORCEMENT OFFICERS; POLICE; BLOCK, SHERMAN; CALIFORNIA NATIONAL GUARD; CRIME 
PREVENTION 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
