</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Georgia Supreme Court ruled that a 33-year-old quadriplegic has a 
constitutional right to withdraw from the breathing apparatus that has kept him 
alive for four years. The court said in a unanimous opinion that Larry McAfee's 
right to discontinue the treatment falls under privacy rights guaranteed by the 
state and federal constitutions. McAfee suffered a severe spinal cord injury in 
a 1985 motorcycle accident that left him a quadriplegic and dependent upon a 
ventilator to breathe. McAfee has said he plans to shut off his ventilator 
after the holiday season. 
