<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEACE OFFICERS UNIT BACKS S.F. DIST. ATTY. FOR ATTORNEY GENERAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The 34,000-member Peace Officers Research Assn. of California Tuesday endorsed 
San Francisco Dist. Atty. Arlo Smith for attorney general. 
</P>
<P>
The organization, the state's main union of police officers, said Smith has the 
record on fighting crime and other issues important to its membership, 
including support of the death penalty. 
</P>
<P>
"From the street officers' perspective, Arlo Smith, we feel, is the best 
candidate for attorney general," said association President Larry Malmberg. 
</P>
<P>
Smith is battling Los Angeles County Dist. Atty. Ira Reiner for the Democratic 
nomination for the state post. Sacramento lawyer Dan Lungren is so far 
unopposed as the Republican candidate. 
</P>
<P>
One association member, who asked not to be identified, was critical of Reiner, 
charging that he "plea bargains away all our hard work" once cases go to court. 
</P>
<P>
A recent California Poll showed that Smith -- who also has been endorsed by the 
National Organization for Women -- gained 10 points between July and October, 
with the number of Democrats preferring Smith jumping from 13% to 23%. In the 
same survey, Reiner's support by Democrats jumped from 33% in July to 36% in 
October. 
</P>
