<HEADLINE>
<P>
EARNINGS: VONS CUTS LOSSES BY 40%, SALES CLIMB 30% 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JUBE SHIVER Jr. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Vons Cos., apparently successfully coping with the financial fallout from its 
acquisition of the Southern California operations of Safeway Stores last year, 
reported improved results Tuesday, with third-quarter losses about 40% below 
their levels a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
El Monte-based Vons, which acquired 162 Safeway stores in August, 1988, to 
merge into its chain of Vons, Pavilions and Tianguis supermarkets in Southern 
California, reported a net loss of $5.9 million for the 16-week period ended 
Oct. 8, 1989, compared to a net loss of $9.5 million during the third quarter 
of 1988. 
</P>
<P>
"We are extremely pleased with our progress in integrating the Safeway 
operations," said Roger E. Stangeland, chairman and chief executive of Vons. 
"And we anticipate that our performance will continue to improve as we near 
completion of the integration project." 
</P>
<P>
Vons, the largest supermarket chain in Southern California with 334 stores, 
said sales for the third quarter rose 30% to $1.6 billion. The company also 
announced that it had renovated 68 stores and remodeled 22 of its store 
facilities. During the first three quarters of 1989, Vons opened five new 
stores and closed 21. 
</P>
<P>
Wall Street reacted favorably to Vons' financial news, which was released at 
the beginning of trading Tuesday. Vons shares closed at $15, up 62.5 cents on 
trading on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
Although supermarket rivals Ralphs Grocery Co. and American Stores Co., which 
operates Lucky Stores, are expected to release their quarterly financial 
results later this month, analysts on Tuesday were already predicting that Vons 
was benefiting more from its own good management than any favorable industry 
trends. As a result, many analysts expect Vons to continue to capitalize on its 
acquisition of the 162 Safeway stores. 
</P>
<P>
"The big payoff will come in the next few quarters in terms of accelerating 
results," said Gary M. Giblen, a vice president of Paine Webber. "It's no 
longer a question of 'if' but 'when,' " he said. "Vons made one of the most 
dramatic moves in the history of retailing by doubling their store base with 
the purchase of (Southern California) Safeway. Now they are reaping the 
benefits." 
</P>
<P>
Tom Pirko, president of Bevmark Inc., a Los Angeles-based food and beverage 
industry consultant, was equally optimistic. 
</P>
<P>
"We've watched Vons consolidate a lot of their gains and become stronger," he 
said. "Basically these results show they are over the hurdle." JUBE SHIVER Jr. 
</P>
</TEXT>
