<HEADLINE>
<P>
CONSUMER VIEWS: CONSUMERS; 
</P>
<P>
GOING FOR GOLD AS AN INVESTMENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DON G. CAMPBELL, Campbell is a syndicated columnist and former Times staff 
writer. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: In 1982, I bought gold South African Krugerrands for $444 each. In 
1988 I started selling them, piece by piece, and received $397 to $415 each, 
even though the gold Maple Leaf and other gold coins were going for more than 
$470. I was told by Deak International that the low price of the Krugerrands 
was because of our boycott against South Africa. 
</P>
<P>
Since gold is gold, regardless of what country the gold comes from, please tell 
me if I'm getting ripped off. -- M.D. 
</P>
<P>
Answer: Gold is gold, sure enough, but price is still the measure of the 
equation between demand and supply. And the demand for Krugerrands "has just 
not been there for several years," according to Karen Jennings, manager here 
for Deak International Ltd. 
</P>
<P>
Despite constant arguments that gold is "just another metal," the metal has had 
a hypnotic appeal since the Egyptians discovered it about 4000 BC, and for 
centuries it was the world's "ultimate store of value" and was the backing for 
almost all currencies. Even now, gold is generally regarded as one of the more 
reliable hedges against inflation -- which is why the price of the metal soars 
during periods of high inflation and drops precipitously during periods of 
stable prices. 
</P>
<P>
But holding gold, either as an investment or as an inflation hedge, has always 
presented problems. To hold it in "raw" form, as ingots or dust, is unwieldy 
because it has to be assayed every time you try to sell it. A much better 
solution: Hold it in the form of established coinage, where the gold content is 
clearly a matter of record. 
</P>
<P>
For years, then, investors (as distinguished from numismatists, who collect 
coins for their historic value and their visual condition) concentrated 
principally on two widely circulated international coins -- the Mexican 50 Peso 
Centenario and the Austrian 100 Corona. A third coin, the Hungarian 100 Korona, 
had a limited circulation for reasons that are comparable to the Krugerrand's 
woes -- investors disliked benefiting Hungary's Communist government. 
</P>
<P>
All three coins, though, had one cumbersome feature -- the offbeat weight of 
the coins, which made it difficult to determine their current market value. 
Both the Corona and the Korona are .98 Troy ounce and the Centenario is 1.2 
Troy ounces. 
</P>
<P>
When South Africa, which sits on most of the world's known supply of unmined 
gold, decided in the 1960s to create the Krugerrand, leave it undenominated, 
but peg it at exactly 1.00 Troy ounce, it was an instant hit because of its 
convenience. If you had 100 Krugerrands you had exactly 100 ounces of gold, and 
all you had to do was look up the "spot" price of gold on any given day and 
you'd know exactly what your holdings were worth. 
</P>
<P>
"But, because of their convenience," Jennings adds, "coins traditionally sell 
at a slight premium." 
</P>
<P>
On the day we discussed this, the "spot" price for gold was $367 an ounce and 
Deak was buying the Canadian Maple Leaf (also 1.00 Troy ounce) for $372 -- a 
$5-an-ounce premium -- but was buying the Krugerrand for $357, a $10-an-ounce 
discount. 
</P>
<P>
"But the 'spot' price," she says, "isn't actually the price of an ounce of gold 
that's been melted down, as you might think, but is simply the market 
determination of gold's value on that day." 
</P>
<P>
Because of the Krugerrand's additional convenience of being exactly 1.00 Troy 
ounce, "it was tremendously popular for several years." 
</P>
<P>
But then apartheid and its ugliness flared up, the violence accelerated, and 
the world's growing disillusionment with South Africa's unyielding position on 
racial relations began sharply eroding the Krugerrand's appeal. 
</P>
<P>
"When the Canadians came out with the gold Maple Leaf in the mid, or late, 
'70s," Jennings adds, "it was beautiful timing. Investors really wanted a 
one-ounce gold coin, and for several years Canada practically had a corner on 
the market." 
</P>
<P>
Then Uncle Sam took the hint and came out with the one-ounce Eagle in 1986. "A 
lot of the bigger dealers today," she says, "and we're one of them, won't even 
sell the Krugerrand, and we buy them back only because so many of our customers 
originally bought them from us. We feel obligated." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
